  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: Analyst identified a lower low in price around 22.90–22.95 and compared it to the Stochastic RSI %D line, noting the oscillator formed a higher low at that time — defining this as a regular bullish divergence indicating an upside reversal.",
    "Step 2: Analyst observed the subsequent price rise, then a new higher high near 23.08–23.10, and checked the Stochastic RSI %D, which showed a lower high — identifying this as a regular bearish divergence signaling a potential downside reversal.",
    "Step 3: Analyst confirmed the bearish divergence was followed by a sharp price collapse, validating the signal."
  ],
  "outcome": "Price reversed upward after bullish divergence, then reversed downward sharply after bearish divergence; analyst explicitly stated 'the price completely collapse' post-bearish divergence signal.",
  "lessons": "Bullish divergence (price lower lows, oscillator higher lows) can signal reversals up; bearish divergence (price higher highs, oscillator lower highs) can signal reversals down—especially when using Stochastic RSI %D for cleaner signals.",
